<ns0:entry xmlns:ns0="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom" xmlns:ns1="http://schemas.google.com/g/2005" xmlns:ns2="http://schemas.google.com/projecthosting/issues/2009" ns1:etag="W/&quot;A04HR347eCl7ImA9WhFTFUg.&quot;">
		<ns0:id>http://code.google.com/feeds/issues/p/nativeclient/issues/full/2832</ns0:id><ns0:author>
			<ns0:name>mseaborn@chromium.org</ns0:name><ns0:uri>/u/mseaborn@chromium.org/</ns0:uri></ns0:author><ns0:content type="html">Chromium has been split up into &amp;quot;content&amp;quot; and &amp;quot;chrome&amp;quot; directories, and &amp;quot;content&amp;quot; has a set of public #include files in &amp;quot;content/public&amp;quot; that &amp;quot;chrome&amp;quot; is allowed to use.  &amp;quot;chrome&amp;quot; isn't allowed to #include other headers from &amp;quot;content&amp;quot;, and this is enforced by checkdeps.py.

We should do something similar for NaCl.  That is, put header files that Chromium may use into &amp;quot;native_client/public&amp;quot;.

This should reduce problems with updating nacl_revision in Chromium's DEPS, because it should make it more obvious what changes could affect the Chromium build.  (For example, recently, https://src.chromium.org/viewvc/native_client?view=rev&amp;amp;revision=8770 required a Chromium change other than changing DEPS, but it wasn't obvious in advance.)

However, I expect that the (deprecated) SRPC-based PPAPI proxy will be exempted from this checkdeps constraint, since it depends on SRPC and lots of other stuff.
